    "code": "R10.9",
    "rawCode": "R109",
    "shortDesc": "Unspecified abdominal pain",
    "longDesc": "Unspecified abdominal pain",
    "plainEnglish": "This code means a patient has stomach or belly pain, but the doctor hasn't identified the specific cause or location yet. It could be anywhere in the abdomen—upper, lower, left, or right—and could result from many things like indigestion, muscle strain, gas, or something more serious that needs further investigation. The pain might be sharp, dull, cramping, or aching, and without more specific examination or testing, the doctor simply documents it as general abdominal discomfort.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, emergency medicine doctors, and urgent care clinicians use this code when patients report belly pain but the initial evaluation hasn't pinpointed a definitive cause. This code commonly appears on patient EOB statements as a temporary or initial diagnosis code while the patient awaits further testing or specialist evaluation.",
