    "code": "R41.3",
    "rawCode": "R413",
    "shortDesc": "Other amnesia",
    "longDesc": "Other amnesia",
    "plainEnglish": "Other amnesia refers to memory loss that doesn't fit into more specific categories of amnesia, such as loss of memories from a particular time period or difficulty forming new memories. This can result from various causes including brain injury, illness, medication side effects, or psychological trauma. A person with this condition may struggle to recall important information, events, or skills, which can significantly impact their daily functioning and quality of life.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, psychiatrists, and primary care physicians commonly use this code when documenting memory problems that don't have a clearly defined cause or type. It typically appears on EOB statements when a patient undergoes evaluation for unexplained memory loss, cognitive complaints, or post-treatment cognitive issues, and often accompanies referrals for neuropsychological testing or brain imaging.",
