    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a fever (elevated body temperature, usually above 100.4°F or 38°C) when the doctor cannot determine what's causing it. Fever is your body's natural response to infection, inflammation, or other problems, but this code is used when the specific reason for the fever hasn't been identified or documented. It's a temporary symptom that usually goes away once the underlying cause is found and treated.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, urgent care providers, and emergency medicine doctors commonly use this code when patients present with fever but testing hasn't yet identified the cause (such as a specific infection). It frequently appears on patient EOBs, especially for quick office visits or ER encounters where the fever is noted but further diagnosis is pending.",
