    "plainEnglish": "Syncope is a fancy medical term for fainting—a sudden, temporary loss of consciousness where you briefly black out and may fall down. It happens when your brain temporarily doesn't get enough blood flow, usually due to a sudden drop in blood pressure, dehydration, standing up too quickly, extreme fear or pain, or heart rhythm problems. You might feel dizzy, lightheaded, or see spots before it happens, and afterward you typically wake up within seconds to a minute feeling confused or exhausted.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine doctors, cardiologists, neurologists, and primary care physicians use this code when evaluating patients who have fainted or collapsed. It's very common on EOB statements for emergency room visits or urgent care encounters, as syncope is a frequent reason people seek immediate medical attention, though doctors must determine whether it's caused by benign factors like dehydration or something more serious involving the heart or nervous system.",
